  "prompt": "Are there any satellites recovered from space?",
  "response": "Yes, there have been several satellites recovered from space, though it's a relatively rare and complex undertaking. Here are some prominent examples:\n\n*   **Corona Reconnaissance Satellites:** These were a series of US spy satellites launched from 1959 to 1972. They used film cameras to photograph Soviet territory and other areas of interest. After the film was exposed, it was loaded into a re-entry capsule that was ejected from the satellite and recovered mid-air by specially equipped aircraft as it parachuted back to Earth. This was a very successful program, with many successful film capsule recoveries.\n\n*   **Genesis Sample Return Mission:** This NASA mission launched in 2001 and returned a sample of solar wind to Earth in 2004. While the mission itself had a rough landing due to parachute failure, the capsule containing the solar wind samples was recovered (albeit with some damage).\n\n*   **Stardust Sample Return Mission:** Launched in 1999, Stardust collected samples of dust from Comet Wild 2 and interstellar dust. It returned to Earth in 2006, and its sample return capsule was successfully recovered.\n\n*   **Hayabusa and Hayabusa2:** These Japanese missions successfully returned samples from asteroids. Hayabusa landed on asteroid Itokawa in 2005 and returned a sample to Earth in 2010. Hayabusa2 visited asteroid Ryugu and returned a larger sample in 2020.\n\n*   **Crewed Spacecraft:** Manned spacecraft like the space shuttle orbiters and capsules of the Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, Soyuz, Shenzhou and Dragon crew capsules are satellites recovered from space.\n\nThese missions highlight the complexity and challenges of retrieving objects from space. While sample return missions are becoming more common, the recovery of entire satellites remains infrequent due to cost, complexity, and the fact that most satellites are designed to operate until their end-of-life and then deorbit to burn up in the atmosphere.",
